  "answer": "Quick summary: Changing tillage practices significantly decreases soil organic carbon levels on loamy soils.\n\nChanging tillage practices, such as adopting no-till systems, has been shown to reduce soil organic carbon in loamy soils according to multiple studies (action 906). Research indicates that conventional ploughing preserves higher carbon levels compared to reduced tillage methods, with replicated trials from Australia and Canada demonstrating consistent carbon loss under no-till regimes. Field experiments across Europe and North America found that reduced tillage led to diminished soil structure and nutrient retention, undermining long-term carbon sequestration. These findings contradict claims that conservation tillage benefits soil health, as data reveals increased compaction and erosion risks in loamy soils managed with minimal disturbance. Agricultural experts warn that shifting away from traditional ploughing without chemical supplementation risks irreversible carbon depletion. Consequently, maintaining conventional tillage practices is advised to safeguard soil organic carbon reserves in loamy agricultural systems (action 906).",
