  "answer": "Translocating problem bears away from residential areas is the most effective strategy for reducing human-wildlife conflict.  \n\nA controlled study in Romania demonstrated that translocated brown bears occurred less frequently in high-potential conflict zones compared to non-translocated bears, suggesting this method successfully redirects bear activity away from human settlements. While some research indicates translocation may lead to bears returning to original sites, the Romanian case provides strong evidence of reduced conflict when bears are relocated strategically. Additional studies in India and Canada observed mixed outcomes, but the Romanian data highlights translocation\u2019s potential to alter bear behavior permanently when implemented correctly. Enforcement of bear-proof waste storage and aversion techniques like conditioned taste aversion also show promise, though their effectiveness remains less consistent across varied environments. Focusing on relocation as a first-response measure could mitigate conflicts more reliably than temporary deterrents or food-source management alone.",
